name: Prof. Dr.
loan_because: The only way for people (and families, villages, and countries) to survive and increase their standard of living is to have access to and build upon capital. The NY Times bestselling book The End of Poverty by Jeffrey Sachs is must reading for everyone who is interested in Kiva, microlending, or helping others in the "third world." Kiva members: please be aware that only supporting microfinance as the sole solution for ending extreme poverty is wrong. Without extended directed humanitarian relief (such as health care, food, etc) and foreign support for public investment (in health care, education, family planning, infrastructure, administration, etc) microlending can only have limited effectiveness and the poverty trap CANNOT BE BROKEN. Urge your elected officials to actually fund the commitments that the US and many other countries have made to the Millenium Development Goals (MDG)! See: http://devdata.worldbank.org/atlas-mdg/ for MDG data. Hans Rosling on development (AV presentations): http://www.ted.com/index.php/talks/view/id/92 http://www.ted.com/index.php/talks/view/id/140 Jeffrey Sachs (audio lectures): http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/reith2007/ There are opportunities and dilemmas in providing access to capital. In many situations, providing capital (tools and opportunities) can be wonderful; in other situations counterproductive. For example, providing loans for someone to sell an imported good that is unhealthy for the local population and environmentally unsound is ethically troublesome (cigarettes are the perfect example). I hope Kiva and its partners will acknowledge, learn about, and discuss these issues and not try to ignore them. Microlending is in its early stages and still needs research and development to further its helpfulness and sophistication. Funding individuals and organizations through Kiva helps establish the cycle that allows everyone (lenders, lending intermediaries, and borrowers) to learn, build, and learn again to find the right methods and opportunities to create healthful and sustainable change. "Capital as such is not evil; it is its wrong use that is evil. Capital in some form or other will always be needed." Mahatma Gandhi
occupational_info: --teaching the next generation\n--researching to increase our knowledge

name: SusanNepaliKeroseneQueue
occupation: grandma, feminist, liberal activist, and retired landlady
loan_because: "The purpose of life is not to be happy.  It is to be useful, to be honorable, to be compassionate, to have it make some difference that you have lived and lived well."   Ralph Waldo Emerson.
occupational_info: Over the years, I've become a feminist and reproductive and GLBT rights advocate.  I've taught biology, worked as an educator for Planned Parenthood, and been a landlady. I'm married and raised two sons. I"ve lived briefly in Nepal, Yorkshire England, and northern Greece. I've learned to do plumbing (working with water pipes and such), electrical, and other building maintenance tasks.  Now I can spend more time with my grandchildren, fixing up my own house - and being an international microfinancier on Kiva !\n\nAbout my screen name.  When I joined my first team, now called the A+ team, and made a few posts, there was another Susan posting as well.  My profile pic showed me on a ladder doing wiring.  To help people discern which messages belonged to which Susan, I became Susanwithladders.   On our last working trip to Kathmandu, (my husband was working with the Urban Planning Department at the engineering college of Tribhuvan University,  we were there during very severe shortages of all fuels, and rolling electrical blackouts.  One morning  before shops opened, I noticed plastic containers lined up along the curb.  It turned out that the word was that a shipment of kerosene had arrived.  Rather than stand in yet another line, people ran a long cord through the handles of the plastic jugs to keep their jugs' places in the lines.  The photo I took of those jugs seemed to me to be a fitting reminder of how tough life often is for Kiva borrowers.  So, I then became SusanNepaliKeroseneQueue.   The photo is my default profile pic.

occupational_info: I am the owner/founder of Chic Chocolate (pronounced âchickâ) a line of gourmet chocolate bars created just for us Chics.  Growing up with three sisters and raising two girls of my own (and a son - lucky guy!) gave me more than enough insight to the moods, whims, and cravings that make us Chics the unique and fabulous creatures that we are.  \nChic Chocolate started as an idea that grew into an entrepreneurial dream . . . After working in the wine industry, in Sonoma, California, I decided to follow a dream of living in Italy to learn the language, immerse myself in the culture, and enjoy the food and wine throughout the regions.  Ironically, I went to study at a university in Perugia (Umbria), which they tout as being the chocolate capital of the world, and where they hold the worldâs largest chocolate festival every year.  Inspired by my love of wine, my girlsâ personalities (and their chocolate cravings), I came up with the idea to develop a line of chocolate bars just for us Chics . . . because Chics like chocolate (but we wonât hold it against any of you guys if youâre caught eating it!)\nI know first hand what it's like to be raised by a single mom, who wants and needs to take care of herself and her kids.  As a single mom, I have been blessed to be able to realize my dream of starting my own business.  I believe in dreams and I have a heart and vision to give single mothers the freedom to do the same!

name: A+ Team Impact Fund at Foundation Beyond Belief
loan_because: We are the A+ Team Impact Fund at Foundation Beyond Belief (FBB). The A+ Team is the Kiva lending team Atheists, Agnostics, Skeptics, Freethinkers, Secular Humanists, and the Non-Religious. Our mission is to advance the fundamental principle of doing good without relying on a god, and to empower people around the world in attaining the capital and tools they need to meet their own goals. Our purpose is to motivate concerned citizens of the world to support the Fund, to distribute microloans to people living in poverty, and to achieve maximum impact for the donorâs dollar. Our vision is to advance entrepreneurship and to alleviate global poverty and suffering. The A+ Team Impact Fund at FBB will attribute 100% of its loans to the Kiva A + Team.
occupational_info: FBB is a 501(c)(3) organization that has joined forces with the A+ Team at Kiva to create a microlending fund that makes Kiva loans and attributes those loans to the A+ Team, in perpetuity. The Impact Fund at FBB is the fruit of this collaboration. We emphasize supporting loans that are SECULAR, SAFE, AND SHORT-TERM. Funds donated to the Impact Fund will be distributed quarterly to a âlockedâ FBB-controlled and -supported Kiva lending account. We rely on donations to get the funds that we lend. Please consider making a donation to support our efforts. Donations to the Impact Fund may be tax-deductible for U.S. taxpayers who itemize their deductions. (Consult your tax adviser for specifics.) If no receipt for a tax deduction is needed, a Kiva Card can be given to the Impact Fund. Send a Private Message to Captain Craig of the A+ Team with the Kiva Card code and amount. Checks from employers for matching contributions, from Donor-Advised Funds, and from IRA custodians should be sent to: Foundation Beyond Belief, 211 Baker Road #531, Barker, TX 77413. Telephone: 832-464-7006. The check should be made payable to âFoundation Beyond Belief A+ Team Impact Fund.â The Employer Identification Number (EIN) of FBB is 26-4822541. To learn more about the Impact Fund, our lending policies, or to make a tax-deductible donation, please visit our website below. Thank you for your support.

name: Polina
loan_because:
I like that in Kiva money circulates and helps many people over and over again. I have committed to "1 loan a day" plan and have stuck with it since 1/1/10 hoping one day to turn this into a life-changing self-sustaining perpetually-lending money circulation machine.

19/10/11 update: It just hit me that I am lending at a rate of 2+loans per day (70+/month). Seems I need to raise the plank and turn it into 3 loans/day by the start of 2012. I will also hit 1000 loans mark right about that time too so it will be a major milestone. Also with now a little of $6k in the account, I made $20k worth of loans. If anyone else needs convincing of the magic of Kiva, I don't know what else to say.

1/1/11 update: This has turned into a life-changing self-sustaining perpetually-lending money circulation machine much sooner than I thought! As of the start of this year I do not need to put in any more money into kiva and with the balance of only $5600 I relend my repayments at a rate of just over 1 loan a day. Yeepeee!!

Next goal for the end of 2011 (taking advantage of the "estimated repayment" stats page) to have enough money in kiva so that estimated repayments over the next 3 months total my minimum living expenses (aka "rainy day fund"). So instead of the fat banks getting even fatter off my savings Kiva entrepreneurs can put food on their family's tables. Yeehaa!
occupational_info: work? what work?.. I run a web design company for a couple of hours a day and the rest of the time I cook, read, garden, hang out and do nothing - life is paradise!

loan_because: We  like to help people out of poverty by giving them more control over their futures.
occupational_info:
We started in Autumn 2009 by wanting to create our own microfinance 
bank after researching microfinance as part of the IB Geography course. Once we found Kiva, we decided it would be more efficient to use Kiva and concentrate our energy on raising money to lend. At first we decided to raise money by recycling mobile 'phones. This raised our first Â£1304 in April 2010 as part of the biennial Make A Difference Day. In Spring 2011, we entered a second round of mobile 'phone recycling which raised Â£1212.50. So far we had raised the money without directly asking people for financial donations, which we liked.

In Spring 2011 a group of 3 students entered the school's Chiara charity competition and won 80% of the prize fund for Kiva (Â£8000!). This significantly increased our seed fund and meant that all members of the school are able to be involved in choosing entrepreneurs to lend to and track their progress.

Our next core funding boost came in December 2011, from a group of pupils who formed their own business, called Icon, as part of the King's Enterprise Challenge. They sourced and sold bespoke clothing such as hooded tops, which they sold to other pupils. They contributed their profit of Â£240 to our Kiva fund, an especially generous gesture, given how hard they had worked to earn the money.

We were thrilled to pass through the 1000 loan mark around Christmas 2011.

In February 2012, we undertook our next episode of recycling, which involved collecting unwanted CDs, DVDs and computer games. This yielded over Â£1400 for our overall fund.

We were very pleased to break the $50,000 mark in terms of loans made in August 2012!

We hit the 2000 loan mark on September 25th 2012!

We took part in Make A Difference Day 2012 on October 5th at King's. We were collecting unwanted phones, CDs, DVDs, computer games and MP3 players, raising a total of Â£1162.67!

We hit the 2500 loan mark on 26th February 2013!

We were pleased to reach the $100,000 lent mark on 17th March 2014, just after another successful collection of unwanted items for recycling as part of the school's Environment Week. This raised Â£740.57!

Another initiative in early July 2014 was to sell unwanted textbooks from leaving students. This raised Â£193.14!

We collected unwanted things again in October 2014 for Make A Difference Day, raising Â£866.06!

We made our 5000th loan on 17th May 2015!

We made our 6000th loan on 18th August 2016!

name: AMIRALI
loan_because:
Since I have been in the same situation previously, I fully understand the desires and hopes of these individuals as entrepreneurs to fulfill their aspirations, ambitions and achieve their vision to grow in this world like anybody else and be proud of it.

My mentor always preached that: All men, rich and poor, must aid one another materially and personally.
This fraternity is absolute, and it comprises men of any color or creed.
All men irrespective of their color or creed are the sons of Adam in the flesh
and all carry in them spark of the Divine Light.

Everyone should strive his best to see that this spark be not extinguished
but rather developed to the full Companionship-on-High.

One should, by example of their own higher enlightenment and co-operative movement within  themselves set to the world an example of better fraternity and brotherhood which alone can free men from the fear and dangers of moral and mental discord which leads to disaster for all.

He further says, that "You must remember that life will have for you many disappointments. If one-fifth of oneâs hopes are realized, one is extremely lucky and fortunate, so do not be discouraged by disappointments. Failures should be forgotten and new efforts made. Despondency is a sin, and hope, a necessary part of faith both for material wealth and, above all, for progress to spiritual enlightenment.â

Furthermore he made it clear that âStruggle is the meaning of life. Defeat or victory is in the hands of God, but struggle itself is manâs duty and should be his joy.â

From a very young age, I have wanted to help others in whatever way I could, however, I never thought that I would be able to help others in need by micro financing which I would have preferred, but for me, administratively, it would have been impossible.

By micro financing, Kivaâs member partners are indemnifying the Kivaâs lending partners in various countries around the world to offer a loan to their qualified applicants at favorable terms to uplift an entrepreneur with a vision and the intent that most likely the loan will be paid back to the lending partner by the needy entrepreneurs and, subsequently, to member partners, minus any losses such as foreign currency rate fluctuations, default in payments or delinquent payments.

Looking forward, I will keep on funding additional entrepreneurs thereby multiplying my original contribution to support more entrepreneurs. For anyone who wants to participate in the Kivaâs lending program and have the joy and the inner feelings of helping the needy entrepreneurs with dreams, this is the right fraternity to do so. 

I never thought that someone, one day like Kivaâs administrators, would walk in and make it administratively possible.  Therefore, I am extremely fortunate and thankful to the creators of Kiva.org for extending an opportunity to my family and me to be a part of such a magnificent fraternity through which we can participate in extending our help to others in need to fulfill their visions and dreams.  I feel I am very fortunate for this opportunity and would like to assure Kiva.org that we are committed to support them and will always be steadfast to them as long as we have the means to do so.







.
occupational_info: I have been an entrepreneur  in Dallas Texas for the past 40 years.\n\nI have been blessed with a wonderful wife,three sons,two daughter in laws and four grandchildren.

Some keywords to describe me and my life: Karoline. Female. 25. Norway. Jesus. Travelling. Concerts. Literature. Global health. Africa. Children. Iced coffee. Music. Movies. Clouds. History. Scarves. Languages. Fulham FC. Nepal. Maternal and Child Health. Volunteering. Animals. Cello. Life. Faith. Hope. Love.

Received my BA in Development Studies from University of Oslo in June 2012. I've lived in the US, studied in London (SOAS) and India, volunteered in Ghana and done field work in Botswana. Last year I interned for six months at the Royal Norwegian Embassy in Kathmandu, Nepal then interned for three months at UNFPA Geneva.

Then studied MSc Demography and Health at London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine. I am now a Research Assistant working on data analysis on immigrants and suicide at Norwegian Institute of Public Health.

I just can't see myself doing anything else than help other people unlock the incredible volumes of human capital in this world.

name: Kemuel
loan_because:
Growing up in St.Vincent West Indies, I was always curious about how the movies I would see in theaters were made. After arriving in the United States over 30 years ago, I first began as a wedding photographerâs assistant after attending my first wedding in 1990. I learned how to create emotions through a lens in the 4 stages of a wedding, home, church, park, and reception. 

 Always evolving,  my passion for shooting, lead to me enrolling into media arts by attending School Of Visual Arts where I got my degree in filmmaking in 2003.
By working my way through the entertainment business I gain real world  experience how to make my own short films. YES!!!, through school and life experiences, I now knew how those movies I saw as a boy were made.

I created KMPearl Productions in 2004 because my passion for bring something to life and sharing with the world grew as I wrote, directed, and edited my own projects beginning in 2006. I fully realized my motivation for shooting empathy stories comes from my many years as a wedding photographer. One of the reasons audiences enjoy my stories is because of their subject matter,  dramatic and spiritualâ¦films you can experience together as a family.

When I am not shooting a film, I would shoot for others who has need of my services. As a an independent filmmaker, one of the best tools you can have at your immediate disposal are great lenses. To rent them at times takes 2 days to ship out, and requires taking out a million dollar insurance policy. Often our company would get a call for a shoot that has to be done the next day. I would like to continue to produce great looking projects not only for myself, but for anyone by having immediate access to great quality lenses.
occupational_info:
I am a New York-based filmmaker, photographer, writer and director with over ten years of media experience. Recently credited as the writer, director & producer of the short film â In The Balanceâ which is based on the highly controversial topic of Post Traumatic Stress Disorder.

I began my professional career working as a Data Entry Supervisor for Chase Bank and after 15 years decided to follow my spiritual and artistic passion by earning  a Bachelorâs of Fine Arts degree from New Yorkâs School of Visual Arts. Among my many industry credits are âBETâs Rip The Runwayâ, âNobodyâs Perfectâ, âSingle Hillsâ, âWomen Do It Betterâ, âUnidentifiedâ as well as principal photography and videography for Marcus Samuelsson of Harlemâs premiere restaurant, The Red Rooster.

I believe myself distinguished among modern videographers and filmmakers by two signature characteristics: (1) my spiritually infused passion for great films and (2) my unparalleled background that combines corporate professionalism with visual creativity. Works of great spiritual infused beauty such as, âThe Green Mileâ, âPowderâ, Forrest Gump, and âFar from Homeâ are  works that have most influenced and touched him as an artist.

With every purchase from you, GCB invests 5% of its profit for a poor family.  

Our charity program donates to more than 50 countries through our partner NGOs with KIVA. 

Our partner NGOs were selected because of their long term, social interventions that address the real root of poverty in these areas in order to help needed communities start or grow a business, go to school, access clean energy or realize their potential. For some, itâs a matter of survival, for others itâs the fuel for a life-long ambition.

name: Mark Agwonah Memorial
loan_because:
This is a lending group in memory of Kiva borrower Mark Agwonah, who contributed greatly to his community and was tragically lost to the Kiva family on July 15th, 2007 under mysterious circumstances.

Mark Agwonah was 30 years old and an only son. He left behind his mother and two dependents, a boy and a girl, who are members of his extended family. The parents of one of the dependent died due to HIV/AIDS and the other dependent was abandoned during the 1992 land clashes in the Transmara region of Kenya. 

Mark was the founding member of a program called Youth Empowerment Centre. The Centre educates young men and women to help them start small businesses and also supports them with small loans.
occupational_info:
We are a group of people from  www.kivafriends.org, who were shocked and outraged by what happened to Mark and want to ensure his legacy by making loans to Kenya. Mark has been an inspiring example for many and we do not want his legacy to fade.

The brutal death of a member of our community is a blow to all of us. If you want to join us, go to www.kivafriends.org/index.php/topic,682.0.html and post there. 

We also set up a fund to support Mark's mother, who is now solely responsible for the two children. If you want to know more, please go to:
www.kivafriends.org/index.php/topic,857.0.html

name: Paresh
occupational_info:
PK is a real estate developer, film producer, investor and philanthropist. As the founder and CEO of Oasis Enterprise, he owns & operates hotels in the California Bay Area, as he continues a lifelong mission to pay-it-forward by creating new opportunities for those seeking to improve their situation. 
He began in modest fashion, learning all aspects of the hotel industry from the ground up, making the most of a hands-on education in hospitality operation & management.  His fourth hotel is currently under construction for a late 2017 ribbon cutting.  
His life-long love of film has lead him into film & video production with short films and feature projects in development, including a quasi-biographical drama, a horror feature and more in the pipeline.
Currently PK is on the Board of Directors of the Oakland Convention Centerâs Visitor Bureau, a standing member with CREW, and the Chambers of Commerce in both Oakland and Alameda, as well as long-term member of The Indus Entrepreneurs (TiE).  As an ambassador for American Asian Hotel Owner Association (AAHOA) he nurtures new opportunities and business developments in that industry.   
PKâs Vision is to inspire others, helping them to develop out of the box thinking that will become a driving force for social, environmental and the economic benefit of all.  
Inspiration for Tomorrow, Opportunities for Today.

name: Reliable Education
loan_because:
*EVERY TIME A NEW STUDENT JOINS WE MAKE A LOAN THROUGH KIVA* 

At Reliable Education we believe that opportunity is something that everyone should enjoy. 

That's why for every new student that joins the Reliable Income Academy we make an interest free micro-loan to an entrepreneur in a third world country. 

These loans enable people to buy seeds to grow crops, inventory to expand stores or equipment to increase efficiencies. 

When the loan is re-paid we lend it again which keeps the good going.
occupational_info:
*WE BELIEVE IN HELPING GOOD PEOPLE DO GREAT THINGS*

Reliable Education is a global eCommerce education company dedicated to helping people launch and grow their own successful businesses on the Amazon platform. 

Reliable Education has differentiated itself within the online education space by setting realistic expectations with regards to the time and capital required to grow a profitable Amazon business.

When students are approved into the Reliable Income Academy they gain access to a global community of like-minded professionals and a body of knowledge that is not uncomfortable with discussing the hard realities or the true numbers around launching and growing a successful business.

Reliable Education currently trains Amazon sellers in 15 different countries including the USA, UK, Canada, Australia, New Zealand, Singapore, Spain, South Africa, Brazil and Switzerland.

Adam Hudson & Joe Olejnik

name: Denver-Nairobi Sister Cities
loan_because:
Denver, Colorado and Nairobi, Kenya established a Sister Cities partnership on March 2, 1975.  The mission of Denver Sister Cities International is to promote peace through mutual respect, understanding and cooperation with cultural, educational and economic endeavors. Through more than 30 years, the Denver-Nairobi Committee has been dedicated to promoting economic achievements, cultural exchanges, and cross-cultural learning opportunities. 

The Denver-Nairobi Committee is excited and honored to be participating in micro-credit lending to individuals strengthening their lives and communities in Kenya.
occupational_info: Denver and Nairobi are both bustling modern capitols, with international air, diverse populations and nearby snow-topped peaks. Nairobi, like Denver, is situated on a high plateau with two of the highest peaks in Africa a relatively short distance away. Nairobi is an exciting and cosmopolitan city and, as the capitol of Kenya, serves as a center of commerce for all of East Africa. Like the "Queen City of the Plains," Nairobi is a beautiful city and has often been referred to as the "Jewel of Africa."
